Here's a minimal API endpoint handling multipart form uploads with multiple images and a description:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size to 50 MB
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the multipart form; set the value-length and body-length limits
    var form = await request.ReadFormAsync(new FormOptions
    {
        MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 50 * 1024 * 1024,
        ValueLengthLimit         = 4 * 1024 * 1024
    });

    var description = form["description"].ToString();
    var files       = form.Files.GetFiles("images"); // matches <input name="images" />

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No image files provided.");

    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var path = Path.Combine("uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(path);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);
        saved.Add(path);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, uploadedFiles = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();   // required for minimal APIs accepting form data without a token

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureKestrel`** — raises the default 30 MB request body limit to 50 MB.
- **`FormOptions.MultipartBodyLengthLimit`** — caps the multipart body at the same 50 MB.
- **`form.Files.GetFiles("images")`** — retrieves all files under the `images` field name.
- **`DisableAntiforgery()`** — needed when the caller (e.g. `curl`, a SPA) won't send an antiforgery token.

**Test with curl:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=My vacation photos" \
  -F "images=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "images=@photo2.png"
```

If you prefer **parameter binding** instead of manual form reading, you can use a typed approach:

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload-typed", async (
    IFormFile[] images,          // bound by name from form fields
    [FromForm] string description) =>
{
    // same processing logic as above
    return Results.Ok(new { count = images.Length, description });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

> Note: `[FromForm]` scalar binding and `IFormFile[]` array binding require .NET 8+.
